Brienne
knew
him
too.
From
behind
her
came
a
rustling
as
a
head
poked
down
through
the
red
leaves.
Crabb
was
standing
underneath
the
weirwood.
He
looked
up
and
saw
the
face.
“Here,”
he
called
to
Brienne.
“It’s
your
fool.”

“Dick,”
she
called
urgently,
“to
me.”

Shagwell
dropped
from
the
weirwood,
braying
laughter.
He
was
garbed
in
motley,
but
so
faded
and
stained
that
it
showed
more
brown
than
grey
or
pink.
In
place
of
a
jester’s
flail
he
had
a
triple
morningstar,
three
spiked
balls
chained
to
a
wooden
