he
came
at
her,
his
feet
sending
up
splashes
of
black
water
as
he
charged.
The
others
stood
back
to
watch
the
show,
as
she
had
prayed
they
might.
Brienne
stayed
as
still
as
stone,
waiting.
The
yard
was
dark,
the
mud
slippery
underfoot.
Better
to
let
him
come
to
me.
If
the
gods
are
good,
he’ll
slip
and
fall.

The
gods
were
not
that
good,
but
her
sword
was.
Five
steps,
four
steps,
now,
Brienne
counted,
and
Oathkeeper
swept
up
to
meet
his
rush.
Steel
crashed
against
steel
as
her
blade
bit
through
his
rags
and
opened
a
gash
in
his
chainmail,
even
as
his
axe
came
crashing
down
at
her.
She
twisted
