and
scowled
at
her,
as
if
challenging
her
to
dispute
his
version
of
events.
“I
am
told
the
Kingslayer
went
through
him
like
an
axe
through
ripe
cheese.
Why
should
my
boys
hurry
south
to
die?
All
those
who
did
go
south
are
running
north
again.”

Catelyn
would
gladly
have
spitted
the
querulous
old
man
and
roasted
him
over
a
fire,
but
she
had
only
till
evenfall
to
open
the
bridge.
Calmly,
she
said,
“All
the
more
reason
that
we
must
reach
Riverrun,
and
soon.
Where
can
we
go
to
talk,
my
lord?”

“We’re
talking
now,”
Lord
Frey
complained.
The
spotted
pink
head
snapped
around.
“What
are
you
all
looking
at?”
he
shouted
at
his
kin.
“Get
out
of
here.
Lady
Stark
wants
to
speak
to
me
in
private.
Might
be
she
has
designs
on
my
fidelity,
heh.
Go,
all
of
you,
find
something
useful
to
do.
Yes,
you
too,
woman.
Out,
out,
out.”
As
his
sons
and
grandsons
and
daughters
and
bastards
and
nieces
and
